\details{
\subsection{Statistical model}{

The General Location Model (Olkin & Tate 1961; Little & Schluchter 1987)
factorises the joint distribution of continuous variables \strong{y} and
categorical variables \strong{x} as:
\deqn{p(\mathbf{y}, \mathbf{x}) =
      p(\mathbf{y} \mid \mathbf{x})\, p(\mathbf{x})}
The categorical margin \eqn{p(\mathbf{x})} is modelled with a log-linear
model restricted to at most \code{cat.interact}-way interactions among the
categorical variables. The continuous conditional
\eqn{p(\mathbf{y} \mid \mathbf{x} = c)} is multivariate normal with a
cell-specific mean vector and a covariance matrix \strong{shared} across all
cells. This model implies that the conditional mean of every continuous
variable is a linear function of every other variable (both continuous and
categorical). The conditional distribution of every categorical variable
is a logistic regression function of every other variable.
}

\subsection{EMB algorithm}{

Proper multiple imputations are generated via the EMB algorithm
(Honaker, King & Blackwell 2011):
\enumerate{
\item Draw a bootstrap sample (with replacement) from the incomplete data.
\item Run the ECM algorithm (\code{\link[mix:ecm.mix]{mix::ecm.mix()}}) on the bootstrap sample to
obtain parameter estimates.
\item Draw one set of imputed values from the posterior predictive
distribution given those parameters (\code{\link[mix:imp.mix]{mix::imp.mix()}}).
\item Repeat steps 1–3 \code{m} times to produce \code{m} completed datasets.
}
}

\subsection{Sparsity}{

When the number of cells in the multiway table for the categorical variables
is large relative to sample size, some cells may contain few or no
observations. A Dirichlet prior (controlled by \code{cat.prior}) is applied by
adding \code{cat.prior} pseudo-observations per cell to the bootstrap sample
before estimation. \code{glemb()} warns when the number of cells exceeds
\code{n / 5}.
}
}
